79 Solo il peccato è quel che la disfranca 80 e falla dissimìle al sommo bene, 81 per che del lume suo poco s’imbianca;
82 e in sua dignità mai non rivene, 83 se non rïempie, dove colpa vòta, 84 contra mal dilettar con giuste pene.

query.result:
85 Your nature, when it sinned totally 86 in its seed, was removed from these dignities, 87 as from paradise;
88 nor can it be recovered, if you consider 89 very subtly, by any way, 90 without passing through one of these fords:
91 either that God alone through his courtesy 92 had forgiven, or that man by himself 93 had atoned for his folly.

112 Neither between the last night and the first day 113 was there ever so lofty or magnificent a process, 114 either by the one way or the other, nor will there be:
115 for God was more generous in giving himself 116 to make man capable of raising himself up, 117 than if he had only forgiven him;
118 and all the other ways were insufficient 119 for justice, if the Son of God 120 had not humbled himself to become incarnate.

